Bills to raise credits and taxes\tab 53.\tab Any bill having as its object the appropriation of any portion of the public revenue, or the creation of taxes or imposts, shall originate in the House of Commons.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Credit recommendation\tab 54.\tab It shall not be open to the House of Commons to pass any resolution, address or bill for the appropriation of any part of the public revenue, or of any tax or impost, for any object which shall not have, at the previously, been recommended to the House by a message from the Governor-General during the session in which such resolution, address or bill is proposed.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Royal assent to bills, etc.\tab 55.\tab When a bill passed by the Houses of Parliament is presented to the Governor-General for the Queen's Assent, the Governor-General shall declare at his discretion, but subject to the provisions of this Act and to the instructions of Her Majesty, or that 'he assent it in the name of the Queen, or he refuses that sanction, or he reserves the bill for service to the Queen's pleasure.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Disallowance by Order in Council of Acts Assented by the Governor General\tab 56.\tab When the Governor-General has given assent to a bill in the name of the Queen, he shall, at the first favorable opportunity, transmit an authentic copy of the law to one of Her Majesty's principal Secretaries of State; if the Queen in Council, within two years after the Secretary of State receives it, deems it advisable to disavow it, this disavowal, - accompanied by a certificate from the Secretary of State, noting the day on which it will have received the law - being served by the Governor General, by speech or message,}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Significance of the Queen's pleasure in respect of reserved bills\tab 57.\tab A bill reserved for the service of the Queen's pleasure shall have neither force nor effect before and unless within two years from the day on which it is presented to the Governor General for the Queen's assent, that time. The latter does not signify, by speech or message, to each of the two Houses of Parliament, or by proclamation, that he has received the assent of the Queen in Council.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
These speeches, messages or proclamations will be recorded in the journals of each chamber, and a duly certified duplicate will be issued to the officer he belongs to for deposit among the archives of Canada.}
