Appointment of executive officers for Ontario and Quebec\tab 134.\tab Until the Legislature of Ontario or Quebec orders otherwise, the Lieutenant Governors of Ontario and Quebec may each appoint under the Great Seal of the Province the following officials who will remain in office for good pleasure , namely: the attorney general, the secretary and registrar of the province, the treasurer of the province, the commissioner of crown lands, and the commissioner of agriculture and public works, and, as regards Quebec, the solicitor-general; they may also, by order of the Lieutenant Governor in Council, prescribe from time to time the powers of such officials and of the various departments under their control or to which they report, and of the officers and employees attached thereto; and they may also appoint other officials who will remain in charge during good pleasure, and prescribe, from time to time, their attributions and those of the various departments under their control or to which they report, and of the officers and employees attached to them.(67)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Powers, duties, etc., of executive officials\tab 135.\tab shall be conferred or imposed upon any official who shall be appointed by the Lieutenant Governor for the performance of such functions or any of them; the commissioner of agriculture and public works shall fulfill the duties and functions of minister of agriculture prescribed, at the time of the passing of this law, by the law of the province of Canada, as well as those of commissioner of public works.(68)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Great Seals\tab 136.\tab Until modified by the Lieutenant Governor in Council, the Great Seals of Ontario and Quebec respectively will be the same or according to the same model as those used in the provinces of Upper and Lower Canada respectively before their union as province of Canada.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Interpretation of temporary laws\tab 137.\tab The words "and thence until the end of the next session of the legislature", or other words of the same tenor, employed in a temporary law of the Province of Canada not expired before the union, shall be deemed to mean the next session of the Parliament of Canada, if the object of the law falls within the category of the powers attributed to that Parliament and defined in this Constitution, if not, at the next sessions of the legislatures of Ontario and Quebec respectively, if the object of the law falls into the category of powers attributed to these legislatures and defined in this law.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Wrong quotes\tab 138.\tab Since and after the time of the union, the insertion of the words \u8220\'93Upper Canada\u8221\'94 instead of \u8220\'93Ontario\u8221\'94, or \u8220\'93Lower Canada\u8221\'94 instead of \u8220\'93Quebec\u8221\'94, in any act, writ, procedure, plea, document, matter or thing, will not have the effect of invalidating it.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Proclamations not to take effect until after union\tab 139.\tab Any proclamation under the Great Seal of the Province of Canada, made before the time of union, to have effect from a date subsequent to union, whether relating to that province or to Upper Canada or to Lower Canada, and the various matters and things set forth therein will have and will continue to have the same force and the same effect as if the union had not taken place. (69)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Proclamations launched after the union\tab 140.\tab Any proclamation the issue of which under the Great Seal of the Province of Canada is authorized by any law of the Legislature of the Province of Canada, whether relating to that Province or to Upper Canada or Lower Canada, and which will not have been launched before the time of union, may be launched by the Lieutenant-Governor of Ontario or Quebec (as the case may be), under the Great Seal of the Province; and, from the issuance of this proclamation, the various matters and things set forth therein shall have and shall continue to have the same force and the same effect in Ontario or Quebec as if the union had not taken place. (70)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Penitentiary\tab 141.\tab The penitentiary of the Province of Canada, until the Parliament of Canada orders otherwise, shall be and continue to be the penitentiary of Ontario and Quebec. (71)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Debts referred to arbitration\tab 142.\tab The division and distribution of the debts, credits, obligations, property and assets of Upper and Lower Canada will be referred to the decision of three arbitrators, one of whom will be chosen by the Government of Ontario, one by the government of Quebec, and the other by the government of Canada; the choice of arbitrators will take place only after the Parliament of Canada and the legislatures of Ontario and Quebec have been brought together; the arbitrator chosen by the Government of Canada must not be domiciled in either Ontario or Quebec. (72)}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\dbch\af6\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\hich\af3\fs24\lang1049{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Sharing archives\tab 143.\tab The Governor-General in Council may from time to time order that the archives, books and documents of the Province of Canada which he deems expedient to designate, be delivered and transferred to Ontario or Quebec, and they shall therefore become the property of of this province; any copy or extract of these documents, duly certified by the officer having custody of the originals, will be accepted as proof. (73)}
